e the favorite of the supreme leader for being unable to come to an agreement with the international community and ease any of the sanctions arrayed against iran it is good to have centrifuges running provided people lives and livelihoods are also running he said in debate to great applause since his election rouhani has been sending conciliatory signals every few days he has exchanged letters with obama tweet from twitter account said to belong to the iranian president wished jews everywhere blessed new year he announced that the foreign ministry would take charge of the nuclear negotiations wresting them from the more council he spoke of the importance of flexibility in negotiations with the west and transparency in iran nuclear program which means he would be willing to allow in international inspectors germany der spiegel has reported that he is prepared to shut down the fordow plant altogether in return for relaxation of sanctions of course rouhani is not the man actually running the country that the supreme leader ayatullah ali khamenei who is deeply and but he is also smart and sophisticated politician who wants to stay in power by limiting internal discontent and so on 17 khamenei said iran would engage in heroic leniency to try to come to an agreement with the international community he also affirmed we do not believe in nuclear weapons because of our beliefs not for the sake of the or other countries and when we say that no country should possess nuclear weapons we ourselves are definitely not trying to possess them now of course this could all be camouflage and smoke screen but there is another possibility the international sanctions against iran are hurting the country badly tehran support for bashar assad brutal regime in syria is costing iran money and arms every month and has tarnished its legitimacy at home the arab spring for all its problems has put the spotlight on iran supreme leader who has been in power for 24 years one of the chants heard in tehran two years ago was mubarak ben ali now it time for sayyid ali khamenei in these circumstances defusing some tensions easing the sanctions and reviving the economy would be extremely useful to the regime in tehran at the very least the obama administration should come up with reasonable offer that would signal to the iranian people that if the regime is willing to credibly forswear nuclear weapons ordinary iranians will have brighter future but it is difficult to sound reasonable while you are beating the drums of war
syrian rebels killed or kidnapped hundreds of civilians report says rebel fighters in syria killed at least 190 civilians and abducted more than 200 during an offensive against villages committing war crime an international human rights group said friday the attacks on unarmed civilians in more than dozen villages in the coastal province of latakia were systematic and could even amount to crime against humanity human rights watch said in report based on visit to the area month later witnesses said rebels went house to house in some cases executing entire families and in other cases killing men and taking women and children hostages the villagers belong to the minority alawite sect an offshoot of shiite islam which forms the backbone of president bashar assad regime and which sunni muslim extremists consider heretics one survivor hassan shebli said he fled as rebels approached his village of barouda at dawn but was forced to leave behind his wife who was unable to walk without crutches and his son who is completely paralyzed when shebli returned days later after government forces retook the village he found his wife and son buried near the house and bullet holes and blood splatters in the bedroom the new group said the findings are bound to feed mounting western unease about the tactics of some of those trying to topple assad and about the growing role of jihadi rebels including foreign fighters linked to war crimes investigators have accused both sides in syria civil war now in its third year of wrongdoing though they said earlier this year that the scale and intensity of rebel abuses has reached that of the regime the new allegations of rebel abuses come at time when the regime is regaining some international legitimacy because of its apparent cooperation with an internationally mandated program to destroy syria chemical weapons stockpile by lama fakih of human rights watch said the rebel abuses in latakia certainly amount to war crimes and may even rise to the level of crimes against humanity the group said more than 20 rebel groups participated in the latakia offensive five groups including two linked to al qaeda and others with jihadi leanings led the campaign which appeared to have been funded in part by private donations raised in the persian gulf the report said human rights watch appealed to the gulf states to crack down on such money transfers it also urged turkey rear base for many rebel groups to prosecute those linked to war crimes and restrict the flow of weapons and fighters the syrian opposition must cut ties with the groups that led the latakia offensive the report said most of the alleged attacks on civilians occurred on said the group the campaign began with rebel fighters seizing three regime posts and then the villages after the regime positions fell no troops were left in the alawite villages it took government forces two weeks to recapture all the villages human rights watch said at least 67 of the 190 civilians slain by the rebels were killed at close range or while trying to flee there are signs that most of the others were also killed intentionally or indiscriminately but more investigation is needed the group said the rebels seized more than 200 civilians from the alawite villages most of them women and children and demanded to trade the hostages for prisoners held by the regime the hrw report said the rebel groups that led the offensive included jabhat and the islamic state in iraq and the levant both linked to al qaeda ahrar jaish and suqqor
